runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:203:+- S-002: Two-phase resolution where the effective state-machine name is selected first from rhei-local `**States:**`, inherited `index.panta.md` default, or built-in fallback; then the file is resolved based on the source of that name, with `--state-machine <path>` acting only as a file override that must match the already-selected name.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:205:+  - Reasons: Separates name resolution from file location to avoid layers competing to both name and locate the machine, preserves the invariant that authored declarations select the state-machine name, allows validation and execution to share a pure resolver, and gives deterministic file roots for rhei-local, Panta-inherited, and built-in fallback cases.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:209:+- A-001: A rhei-local `**States:**` declaration takes precedence over an inherited `index.panta.md` project default.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:211:+- A-002: An inherited Panta default applies only when the rhei is inside a Panta project and omits its own `**States:**`.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:219:+- A-006: `index.panta.md` is assumed to provide at most one project-level `**States:**` default unless the broader design introduces scoped defaults.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:225:+  - Options: S-001 treats an explicit invocation override such as `--state-machine` as the highest-priority complete selection. S-002 treats `--state-machine <path>` as a file-level override after name resolution, requiring the file `name` to match the rhei-local, Panta-inherited, or fallback-selected name.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:227:+  - Evidence needed: The existing or intended CLI/API contract for `--state-machine`: does it mean "use this machine instead of declarations" or "load this file for the declared machine"? Also needed: current implementation behavior and any documented examples for validation/execution overrides.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:231:+  - Options: S-001 orders explicit override before rhei-local `**States:**`. S-002 orders name selection from authored declarations first, then allows the explicit path only if it is name-consistent.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:235:+- D-003: File lookup root for a Panta-inherited `**States:**` name.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:237:+  - Options: S-002 resolves an inherited Panta default to `<project>/states.yaml` only, and a child rhei cannot shadow it with a sibling `states.yaml` unless it redeclares `**States:**` locally. S-001 leaves open whether the inherited tier maps to a project-root file, a search path, or some other complete selection mechanism.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:239:+  - Evidence needed: Existing workspace layout conventions and desired Panta policy semantics: does a project default imply a project-root state-machine file, and should child rheis be able to shadow inherited defaults without local `**States:**`?
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:243:+  - Options: S-002 distinguishes a locally declared `**States: rhei**` from an omitted fallback: local declaration can resolve a sibling/workspace `states.yaml` named `rhei`, while omission uses the compiled built-in and ignores discovered files. S-001 only states built-in `rhei` is the final fallback and does not define whether an authored `rhei` declaration should auto-discover a file.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:245:+  - Evidence needed: Existing spec or tests for auto-discovery of `states.yaml` when `**States: rhei**` is declared, plus compatibility expectations for standalone and Directory Workspace plans.
