runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:1:# Disagreement Map - Resolve Panta defaults in state-machine resolution
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:5:- S-001: Single-tier precedence where the explicit invocation override is the highest-priority complete state-machine selection, followed by rhei-local `**States:**`, inherited `index.panta.md` project default, and built-in `rhei` fallback.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:9:- S-002: Two-phase resolution where the effective state-machine name is selected first from rhei-local `**States:**`, inherited `index.panta.md` default, or built-in fallback; then the file is resolved based on the source of that name, with `--state-machine <path>` acting only as a file override that must match the already-selected name.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:11:  - Reasons: Separates name resolution from file location to avoid layers competing to both name and locate the machine, preserves the invariant that authored declarations select the state-machine name, allows validation and execution to share a pure resolver, and gives deterministic file roots for rhei-local, Panta-inherited, and built-in fallback cases.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:15:- A-001: A rhei-local `**States:**` declaration takes precedence over an inherited `index.panta.md` project default.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:17:- A-002: An inherited Panta default applies only when the rhei is inside a Panta project and omits its own `**States:**`.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:25:- A-006: `index.panta.md` is assumed to provide at most one project-level `**States:**` default unless the broader design introduces scoped defaults.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:31:  - Options: S-001 treats an explicit invocation override such as `--state-machine` as the highest-priority complete selection. S-002 treats `--state-machine <path>` as a file-level override after name resolution, requiring the file `name` to match the rhei-local, Panta-inherited, or fallback-selected name.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:33:  - Evidence needed: The existing or intended CLI/API contract for `--state-machine`: does it mean "use this machine instead of declarations" or "load this file for the declared machine"? Also needed: current implementation behavior and any documented examples for validation/execution overrides.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:37:  - Options: S-001 orders explicit override before rhei-local `**States:**`. S-002 orders name selection from authored declarations first, then allows the explicit path only if it is name-consistent.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:41:- D-003: File lookup root for a Panta-inherited `**States:**` name.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:43:  - Options: S-002 resolves an inherited Panta default to `<project>/states.yaml` only, and a child rhei cannot shadow it with a sibling `states.yaml` unless it redeclares `**States:**` locally. S-001 leaves open whether the inherited tier maps to a project-root file, a search path, or some other complete selection mechanism.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:45:  - Evidence needed: Existing workspace layout conventions and desired Panta policy semantics: does a project default imply a project-root state-machine file, and should child rheis be able to shadow inherited defaults without local `**States:**`?
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:49:  - Options: S-002 distinguishes a locally declared `**States: rhei**` from an omitted fallback: local declaration can resolve a sibling/workspace `states.yaml` named `rhei`, while omission uses the compiled built-in and ignores discovered files. S-001 only states built-in `rhei` is the final fallback and does not define whether an authored `rhei` declaration should auto-discover a file.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:51:  - Evidence needed: Existing spec or tests for auto-discovery of `states.yaml` when `**States: rhei**` is declared, plus compatibility expectations for standalone and Directory Workspace plans.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:53:- D-005: Error handling for missing or mismatched state-machine files.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:55:  - Options: S-002 says a non-`rhei` declared name with no matching file is a validation error and never falls back, and a `--state-machine` file whose `name` disagrees with the selected name is a validation error. S-001 needs equivalent error rules if tiers are complete selections, especially for override paths and inherited defaults.
runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:61:Address only D-001 through D-005. First decide the contract of an explicit override: complete state-machine selection or file-only redirection for a preselected name. Then define the file lookup roots and error behavior for rhei-local, Panta-inherited, explicit `rhei`, omitted fallback, and mismatched/missing files so validation and execution can share one deterministic resolver.
