runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:355:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:9:- S-002: Two-phase resolution where the effective state-machine name is selected first from rhei-local `**States:**`, inherited `index.panta.md` default, or built-in fallback; then the file is resolved based on the source of that name, with `--state-machine <path>` acting only as a file override that must match the already-selected name.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:356:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:11:  - Reasons: Separates name resolution from file location to avoid layers competing to both name and locate the machine, preserves the invariant that authored declarations select the state-machine name, allows validation and execution to share a pure resolver, and gives deterministic file roots for rhei-local, Panta-inherited, and built-in fallback cases.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:357:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:15:- A-001: A rhei-local `**States:**` declaration takes precedence over an inherited `index.panta.md` project default.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:358:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:17:- A-002: An inherited Panta default applies only when the rhei is inside a Panta project and omits its own `**States:**`.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:359:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:19:- A-003: The built-in `rhei` state machine is the final fallback when no higher tier selects a machine.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:360:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:25:- A-006: `index.panta.md` is assumed to provide at most one project-level `**States:**` default unless the broader design introduces scoped defaults.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:361:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:29:- D-001: Whether an explicit override selects the effective state machine or only supplies the file for an already-selected name.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:362:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:31:  - Options: S-001 treats an explicit invocation override such as `--state-machine` as the highest-priority complete selection. S-002 treats `--state-machine <path>` as a file-level override after name resolution, requiring the file `name` to match the rhei-local, Panta-inherited, or fallback-selected name.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:363:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:32:  - Why it matters: This determines whether operators can temporarily change the effective state machine for a run, or can only redirect to another YAML file implementing the already-declared machine name. It also changes which mistakes validation can catch when an override is present.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:364:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:33:  - Evidence needed: The existing or intended CLI/API contract for `--state-machine`: does it mean "use this machine instead of declarations" or "load this file for the declared machine"? Also needed: current implementation behavior and any documented examples for validation/execution overrides.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:365:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:37:  - Options: S-001 orders explicit override before rhei-local `**States:**`. S-002 orders name selection from authored declarations first, then allows the explicit path only if it is name-consistent.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:366:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:41:- D-003: File lookup root for a Panta-inherited `**States:**` name.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:367:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:43:  - Options: S-002 resolves an inherited Panta default to `<project>/states.yaml` only, and a child rhei cannot shadow it with a sibling `states.yaml` unless it redeclares `**States:**` locally. S-001 leaves open whether the inherited tier maps to a project-root file, a search path, or some other complete selection mechanism.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:368:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:45:  - Evidence needed: Existing workspace layout conventions and desired Panta policy semantics: does a project default imply a project-root state-machine file, and should child rheis be able to shadow inherited defaults without local `**States:**`?
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:369:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:49:  - Options: S-002 distinguishes a locally declared `**States: rhei**` from an omitted fallback: local declaration can resolve a sibling/workspace `states.yaml` named `rhei`, while omission uses the compiled built-in and ignores discovered files. S-001 only states built-in `rhei` is the final fallback and does not define whether an authored `rhei` declaration should auto-discover a file.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:370:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:50:  - Why it matters: This affects backward compatibility for plans that declare `rhei` but provide a local `states.yaml`, and it determines whether omission and explicit declaration of the default name are observably different.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:371:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:51:  - Evidence needed: Existing spec or tests for auto-discovery of `states.yaml` when `**States: rhei**` is declared, plus compatibility expectations for standalone and Directory Workspace plans.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:372:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:53:- D-005: Error handling for missing or mismatched state-machine files.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:373:./runtime/deliberation/points/point-state-machine-resolution/disagreement-map.md:55:  - Options: S-002 says a non-`rhei` declared name with no matching file is a validation error and never falls back, and a `--state-machine` file whose `name` disagrees with the selected name is a validation error. S-001 needs equivalent error rules if tiers are complete selections, especially for override paths and inherited defaults.
