runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:842:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:360:  - Options: S-001 treats an explicit invocation override such as `--state-machine` as the highest-priority complete selection. S-002 treats `--state-machine <path>` as a file-level override after name resolution, requiring the file `name` to match the rhei-local, Panta-inherited, or fallback-selected name.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:843:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:361:  - Why it matters: This determines whether operators can temporarily change the effective state machine for a run, or can only redirect to another YAML file implementing the already-declared machine name. It also changes which mistakes validation can catch when an override is present.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:844:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:362:  - Evidence needed: The existing or intended CLI/API contract for `--state-machine`: does it mean "use this machine instead of declarations" or "load this file for the declared machine"? Also needed: current implementation behavior and any documented examples for validation/execution overrides.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:845:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:366:  - Options: S-001 orders explicit override before rhei-local `**States:**`. S-002 orders name selection from authored declarations first, then allows the explicit path only if it is name-consistent.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:846:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:370:- D-003: File lookup root for a Panta-inherited `**States:**` name.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:847:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:372:  - Options: S-002 resolves an inherited Panta default to `<project>/states.yaml` only, and a child rhei cannot shadow it with a sibling `states.yaml` unless it redeclares `**States:**` locally. S-001 leaves open whether the inherited tier maps to a project-root file, a search path, or some other complete selection mechanism.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:848:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:374:  - Evidence needed: Existing workspace layout conventions and desired Panta policy semantics: does a project default imply a project-root state-machine file, and should child rheis be able to shadow inherited defaults without local `**States:**`?
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:849:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:378:  - Options: S-002 distinguishes a locally declared `**States: rhei**` from an omitted fallback: local declaration can resolve a sibling/workspace `states.yaml` named `rhei`, while omission uses the compiled built-in and ignores discovered files. S-001 only states built-in `rhei` is the final fallback and does not define whether an authored `rhei` declaration should auto-discover a file.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:850:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:379:  - Why it matters: This affects backward compatibility for plans that declare `rhei` but provide a local `states.yaml`, and it determines whether omission and explicit declaration of the default name are observably different.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:851:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:380:  - Evidence needed: Existing spec or tests for auto-discovery of `states.yaml` when `**States: rhei**` is declared, plus compatibility expectations for standalone and Directory Workspace plans.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:852:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:382:- D-005: Error handling for missing or mismatched state-machine files.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:853:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:384:  - Options: S-002 says a non-`rhei` declared name with no matching file is a validation error and never falls back, and a `--state-machine` file whose `name` disagrees with the selected name is a validation error. S-001 needs equivalent error rules if tiers are complete selections, especially for override paths and inherited defaults.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:854:./runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-aggregate-disagreements-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:390:Address only D-001 through D-005. First decide the contract of an explicit override: complete state-machine selection or file-only redirection for a preselected name. Then define the file lookup roots and error behavior for rhei-local, Panta-inherited, explicit `rhei`, omitted fallback, and mismatched/missing files so validation and execution can share one deterministic resolver.
