runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:2216:./runtime/logs/task-point-language-reference-propose-solutions-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:3271:  including the synthetic inbox rhei, has no local `**States:**` declaration.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:2217:./runtime/logs/task-point-language-reference-propose-solutions-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:3288:- Why chosen: This directly satisfies all stated constraints and both discussions converged on it. It preserves identical scheduling semantics across rhei boundaries while avoiding unnecessary deployment assumptions: implementations may use a shared callable predicate, direct remote state-machine resolution, or an exported readiness result, provided the result is computed from the prior rhei's own state-machine semantics and is fresh or otherwise auditable.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:2218:./runtime/logs/task-point-language-reference-propose-solutions-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:3289:- Alternatives considered: S-002's single shared predicate is strong when local and cross-rhei scheduling run in the same codebase because it reduces drift and simplifies tests, but requiring one shared in-process callable over-constrains cross-process, cross-repository, or serialized/API boundaries. Direct synchronous dependent-side resolution of the prior rhei's state machine is transparent and sufficient, but it is not necessary if the prior rhei exports an equivalent predicate result with explicit state-machine version and freshness/invalidation guarantees. Treating any terminal state as ready was rejected because normalized `cancelled` must not unblock dependent work.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:2219:./runtime/logs/task-point-language-reference-propose-solutions-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:3290:- Remaining uncertainty: The final implementation still needs to specify the freshness and invalidation contract for cached or exported readiness data. If the prior state, prior state-machine meaning, or exported readiness result cannot be resolved reliably, the dependency must remain blocked.
runtime/logs/task-point-state-machine-resolution-discuss-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:2220:./runtime/logs/task-point-language-reference-propose-solutions-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:3291:- Effect on final solution: The final answer must define cross-rhei readiness as the same successful-terminal predicate used by normal scheduling: `final: true` and normalized state not `cancelled`, evaluated with the prior rhei's state-machine semantics. It should prefer a shared predicate where practical, allow direct resolution or an exported/cached readiness result only when behaviorally equivalent and fresh/auditable, and require unresolved, stale, non-final, or normalized-`cancelled` prerequisites to keep dependents blocked.
